06216nam a22008895i 9780748631957DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486319577 a10.1515/97807486319572doi  a(DE-B1597)614408  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0000002bisacsh  aCI 5599qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/18484:1 aJones, Graham, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDeleuze's Philosophical Lineage /cGraham Jones, Jon Roffe. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (426 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction: Into the Labyrinth -- t1 Plato -- t2 John Duns Scotus -- t3 G. W. F. Leibniz -- t4 David Hume -- t5 Immanuel Kant -- t6 Solomon Maimon -- t7 G. W. F. Hegel -- t8 Karl Marx -- t9 Hoëne Wronski and Francis Warrain -- t10 Bernhard Riemann -- t11 Gabriel Tarde -- t12 Sigmund Freud -- t13 Henri Bergson -- t14 Edmund Husserl -- t15 A. N. Whitehead -- t16 Raymond Ruyer -- t17 Martin Heidegger -- t18 Pierre Klossowski -- t19 Albert Lautman -- t20 Gilbert Simondon -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe philosophy of Gilles Deleuze is increasingly gaining the prestige that its astonishing inventiveness calls for in the Anglo-American theoretical context. His wide-ranging works on the history of philosophy, cinema, painting, literature and politics are being taken up and put to work across disciplinary divides and in interesting and surprising ways. However, the backbone of Deleuze's philosophy - the many and varied sources from which he draws the material for his conceptual innovation - has until now remained relatively obscure and unexplored.This book takes as its goal the examination of this rich theoretical background. Presenting essays by a range of the world's foremost Deleuze scholars, and a number of up and coming theorists of his work, the book is composed of in-depth analyses of the key figures in Deleuze's lineage whose significance - as a result of either their obscurity or the complexity of their place in the Deleuzean text - has not previously been well understood. This work will prove indispensable to students and scholars seeking to understand the context from which Deleuze's ideas emerge. Included are essays on Deleuze's relationship to figures as varied as Marx, Simondon, Wronski, Hegel, Hume, Maimon, Ruyer, Kant, Heidegger, Husserl, Reimann, Leibniz, Bergson and Freud.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aPhilosophyxHistory. 0aPhilosophy. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAlliez, Éric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkinson, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaugh, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaulieu, Alain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBogue, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoundas, Constantin V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffy, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlaxman, Gregory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Eugene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerslake, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary